1.2	Activity: Ukraine Energy Efficiency Secretariat and Expert Hub
	Support to the Government of Ukraine with analysis of the draft Law of Ukraine no. 2638 /Amendments to the Law of Ukraine on Air Quality – analyzing its compliance with EU Association Agreement and other international commitments. In addition, the recommendations for the Parliamentary control over the implementation of the recently developed Law of Ukraine on Basics of Monitoring, Reporting and Verification of Greenhouse Gas Emissions were prepared;
	Awareness raising - following communication pieces were published:
	Turning Slavutych into a Solar Town on the potential way forward for generating greener and cleaner energy in the future through collaborative action;
	Ukraine’s environmental priorities in 13 visual infographics depicting the results of research on citizens’ perceptions and priorities in the field of sustainable energy and environment.
	Nationwide public opinion survey to identify citizens’ perceptions and priorities in the field of sustainable energy and environment was conducted;
	Within the awareness raising efforts, on 3 June 2020 an online discussion Energy: No back to normal – lessons and perspectives for the energy sector was organized within the framework of the “Green Agenda and COVID-19” a week-long online environmental marathon. The discussion focused on the COVID-19 collateral implications as an enhancing factor to stimulate the roll out of sustainable energy solutions. 149 participants (45 men, 104 women), including civil society actors, environmental activists, MPs, representatives from governmental and international organizations, joined the event live, and over 10,000 Ukrainians were reached through social media;
	Support to the Government of Ukraine with the development of the energy efficiency policy. Particularly, facilitated the review of the draft Law on Energy Efficiency developed for the implementation of the Energy Efficiency Directive (2012/27/EU) as well as the discussion on the status of energy efficiency reform implementation in Ukraine in line with Association Agreement, Energy Community and their ranking in the policy agenda of Ukraine, key challenges and required steps for the implementation of the Energy Efficiency Directive (2012/27/EU). The discussion engaged a broad range of stakeholders for consultations on the normative definitions, energy efficiency targets, monitoring and control issues, the role of public buildings in energy efficiency mainstreaming, energy efficiency obligatory schemes, energy audits, accounting, energy conversion, transmission and distribution, energy services, awareness-raising and others;
	Analyses and recommendations of the draft Law on Energy Efficiency examining its alignment with the Energy Efficiency Directive (2012/27/EU) upon the request from the then Ministry of Energy and Environmental Protection; 
	Policy advice to the then Ministry of Energy and Environmental Protection on Energy Efficiency First Principle.

